# Use `ptr.Any(...)` for Pointers to Literals

When you need a `*T` from a literal or computed value, use the generic
helper [`ptr.Any`](mdc:server/common/utils/ptr/any.go) instead of
declaring a single-use local variable solely to take its address.

```go
// server/common/utils/ptr/any.go
func Any[T any](obj T) *T { return &obj }
```

## Rules

- **Never** introduce a throwaway local whose only purpose is `&local`.
  Use `ptr.Any(value)` directly.
- This applies to struct-update / patch fields (`*string`, `*int64`,
  `*bool`, enum pointers, …), optional request fields, and any other
  `*T` built from a literal or a one-off expression.
- For a typed numeric literal, write the type explicitly so generic
  inference picks the right `T`: `ptr.Any(int64(0))`, `ptr.Any(int32(1))`.
- Import as `"github.com/superdurable/dex/server/common/utils/ptr"`.

## When NOT to apply

- The pointer must alias an **existing, named variable** that is also
  read/mutated elsewhere (you genuinely need the address of *that*
  variable, not a copy). `ptr.Any` copies, so it's wrong there.
- Taking the address of a struct you already have (`&myStruct`) — that's
  not a literal-to-pointer conversion.

## Examples

<bad>

```go
emptyTimerID := ""
var zeroFireAt int64
update.ActiveDurableTimerID = &emptyTimerID
update.DurableTimerFireAt = &zeroFireAt
```

</bad>

<good>

```go
update.ActiveDurableTimerID = ptr.Any("")
update.DurableTimerFireAt = ptr.Any(int64(0))
```

</good>

## Review checklist

- Reject a local variable declared on one line and only used on the next
  as `&local` — replace with `ptr.Any(...)`.
